page.title: Controlling hardware
page.text: A large portion of today's programming is for embedded microprocessors. Every dish-washer, alarm clock, washing machine, car, phone, etc.\ has one or more microprocessors inside.
Some decades ago, an elevator was controlled by relays. Today, there is a small computer that does everything.
Electrical engineers spend a lot of time programming embedded devices.
You can buy off-the-shelf devices that allow you to control hardware using a USB connection.

page.title: Elevator
page.text: An elevator for three floors.
\dred{Hardware:} Elevator motor, three floor sensors, four call buttons, four call lights, elevator door.

\dred{Software interface:}
\begin{V} from elevator import * init_hardware() set_motor(speed) # -127..127 set_light(num, state) # num 0..3 open_door() close_door() get_button(num) # num 0..3 get_sensor(floor) # floor 1..3 \end{V}

page.title: Controlling the motor
page.text: When the motor is running, we have to continuously check the floor sensors to stop the motor when we arrive at the right floor (or the elevator will shoot out of the shaft and fall off the roof).

page.title: First attempt
Checking buttons and sensors
page.text: When a call button is pressed, the call light should go on immediately, even if the computer is currently ``busy'' monitoring the elevator movement.

page.title: A state machine
page.text: The target floor of a cabin move can change \dred{while} the cabin is moving.
Let's start again at the beginning. At any time, the elevator is in one of the following eleven states:
wait1\\ wait2\\ wait3
waiting at a floor
move12\\ move23\\ move21\\ move32
moving between floors
open1\\ open2up\\ open2down\\ open3
door open

page.title: Implementing the state diagram
page.text: We write a \dred{handler} function for each state. This function will be called repeatedly as long as the elevator is in this state. When the state changes, we start calling the next handler function.

page.title: Handler functions
page.text: Each handler function must check all call buttons so that the elevator is responsive. It then checks if the state changes, and updates motor, lights, and doors correspondingly.
